USA: Repeating is the mother of wisdom
It is comical, with what kind of schoolwork effort Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor in Afghanistan, which he himself considered to be the dumbest.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he copied it through a copycat from Bush’s Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate to use the name Bush's statement of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New way forward".
Three years ago, he himself criticized Bush's idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to Iraq plagued by civil war as "unresponsible and in his consequences a catastrophic decision".
However, the following months have shown that Bush’s strategy based on the recommendations of field commanders was the only possible and very successful one so far that there is no talk of Iraq in news relations today.
It did not improve Bush’s reputation, but he objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting point than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will repeat itself.
He was asked to increase his military contingent once again by field commanders, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, despite subordinating practices, harshly criticized hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn't find anything better, so at least he cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to squeeze another 5,000 out of Europe, even though he originally counted at least 10.
The most problematic thing about Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and end this process within three years.
Many doubt that a half-increase will yield the same fruit as the advance in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honor agreements.
The Afghan situation is marked by the opposite sign - no one can be relied on and no agreements are observed.
Under these conditions, Afghan security forces used to change masters every day are poorly prepared, depending on how convenient it is for them.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain just a Potemkin village for which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of various ethnic groups is extremely difficult given the ambiguity of the conditions that complicate even more Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Nor does the construction of an "actable state", which is the minimalistic objective of the entire operation, seem to be too real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of an explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent to war for the purpose of "early return home" will produce a miracle here, only the soul can truly romantic, truly intact.
Politically speaking, determining the date of military withdrawal is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will see this as an indirect confession of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is coming to a close.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their voters how the safety of Germany or Italy relates to the war in the foothills of Hindukush.
The development of events around Iran is another factor able to intervene radically.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the reinforced sanctions do not affect the Iranians, there will be a difficult question before the United States whether or not to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will need to be answered at the time that Obama says America will move on to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also entail a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only Band-Aid for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left in the presidential election, and therefore there is enough time left to come up with another strategy if this one turns out to be a total failure.
