Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'hardened' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity from drugs.
This fact in some cases outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on the common variant of the virus as some medicines already available.
AIDS disease cannot be cured yet.
However, patients may be significantly extended by a mixture of medicines that prevent HIV from multiplying in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of virus reproduction results in the development of so-called resistant viruses against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way for the resistance of the virus to be dealt with.
They have shown that a substance called metal carborans acts on the protein responsible for the proliferation of HIV.
Metal-carboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that is different from all medicines currently in use, so they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists come up with new 'improved' compounds prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metal carborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV virus fission, mature infectious viral particles would not occur.
When we stop HIV protease, we stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain that is further systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable.
The effect of this series of anti-HIV protease substances has been tested in the test tube as well as against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of metalocarborans on the normal enzyme variant is not as strong as with clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modification, makes metacarborans interesting compounds for further research towards the design of effective anti-HIV drugs, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
