The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-reaching indiscreet attitudes and mutual appeals -- again on Friday, focused on releasing a document that proposes an ambitious reduction of greenhouse gases over the next 40 years with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden in the near term.
The text, which can provide a starting point for the final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, emphasises the remaining obstacles as well as illuminates the way forward.
But important progress was seen in the negotiations that took place at the wrong time with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Created by the UN ad hoc working group, this text quietly states how much money rich countries should provide to the poor to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a whole range of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies in order to limit their carbon output and what should be the upper limit of the rise in global temperature that political officials will still be able to tolerate.
That adds a great deal of flexibility to the process, says John Coequyt, head of the Sierra Washington Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed a six-page document, crisscrossed from 180 pages of text from the meeting to focus on what a top climate officer at the UN, Yvo de Boer, described as a "big picture".
It outlines the outlines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations could jointly limit their emissions to 25 to 45 percent in comparison to 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent during this period.
Together, the country would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union has discussed urgently on Friday the promise to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to climate change -- from managing floods and drought to preventing deforestation.
