The Turkish Constitutional Court decided on Friday to abolish the main pro-Kurd party in the country. This decision immediately sparked protest demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand and thus try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it became "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said Hasim Kilic, President of the Supreme Court, after four days of negotiations.
The decision was adopted unanimously by 11 Judges, when it was necessary to dissolve the party with a majority of seven votes, Kiliç stated and added that 37 party cadres, including its President Ahmet Türk, and Aysel Tugluk, were banned from participating in political life for a period of five years.
