Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: Animal two metres long and 1.50 meters high ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short front limbs with sickle claws and long tail.
If this species lived a few million years later, there would be nothing special.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas, Austin, and colleagues in the Thursday edition of Science magazine write that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body traits.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today’s New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry area of the Pangea supercontinent.
Tawa opens a new window for the previous evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about kinship, expansion, and signs of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating in Ghost Ranch, north of New Mexico.
Sometimes in one day we found a dozen dinosaur bones, which is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports a member of the Randall Irmis team from the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains from a total of five individuals.
The discovery confirms the theory of the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual finding: "The photos of the dinosaurs from the Triassic are very rare, mostly they only find individual fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
A particularly sensational finding is not, but confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
In the current scientific view, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of Pradinosaurs is usually questionable.
Experts discuss, for example, when lizards were divided into three of the most important development lines: carnivorous terrapods, which later included Tyranosaur Rex, Velociraptor, as well as birds, "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and herbivores Ornithischia (birds), such as Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
Tawa hallae is after the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues the original terapod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
Researchers, for example, found evidence of air sacs on the skull of Tawa hallae, which even the offspring of the terrapods have birds.
Thanks to air bags, bird breathing is more effective than mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive teropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air bags and light bones, this useful innovation was probably already created by the common ancestor of both groups.
