75% of working mothers have maternal problems.
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among women of younger years who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Floorship and career of Spanish women' carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute of Women.
The study was attended by 9.737 women aged 15 to 75 years and results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited labour market opportunities due to motherhood.
The study emphasizes that at the beginning of the partnership there are many differences in the opinion of the number of children according to whether they work or not and also according to the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have stable jobs, start living with a partner earlier, sooner give birth to the first child, and generally have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, partner cohabitation and motherhood, postpone and have fewer offspring.
"Women from 35 to 49 years of age with stable employment have the first child on average 3.7 years from the start of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted more of their lives to achieving stable employment and have therefore had to postpone their partnership cohabitation as well as the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less influence on the time of starting cohabitation with a partner", explains Margarita Delgado, who is involved in research in CSIC.
Another factor affecting women’s age at the time of marriage and birth is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age when women get married and have their first child.
The differences are also among women of the same generation.
For example, between 35 and 49 years of age, women with basic and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25,1 or 32.1.
"There is another difference between women depending on their degree of education.
Women with basic education get married and give birth to the first child before they find a stable job, while women with medium or high education go the other way around prefer to get a stable job, before they marry and the birth of the first child," says Delgado.
