The auxiliary system for the handbrake is already mandatory equipment.
As with the ABS anti-lock system, it will be with ESP stability control, handbrake auxiliary systems, all of which will become mandatory equipment for European vehicles.
In fact, it already forms part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while the others have a deadline for eliminating the shortage, which is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU aim to increase the protection of pedestrians, which can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary hand brake system increases the brake pressure in an emergency, which the system will detect when the driver steps down.
But he can't always hold this pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of Bosch car parts, a third of the drivers who had an accident did not hit the brake before the crash and half of them did not take full advantage of the brake strength.
Up to 1.100 accidents
On the other hand, this assistance requires maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1 100 fatal pedestrian-related accidents per year could be avoided.
The reduction of this number will be even more significant-according to calculations would prevent one of the four accidents affecting persons-after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, vehicles will be equipped with a system that (by radar or camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver responds, he will be helped to increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device will act as intensively as possible on the brake and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
